[1] India (Madhya Pradesh)
Date: Thu 8 Oct 2009
Source: Prokerala.com, Indo-Asian News Service (IANS) report [edited]
<http://www.prokerala.com/news/articles/a84419.html>


Mosquitoborne dengue fever is fast spreading in Madhya Pradesh, with the
disease having claimed at least 9 lives in the past 3 months and affecting
more than 300 people, health officials said on Thursday [8 Oct 2009].

Though at least 192 cases of dengue have been confirmed by the Bhopal-based
Gandhi Medical College alone, the district malaria officer Padmakar
Tripathi last week [week of 28 Sep 2009] put the figure at 103 confirmed
cases. The government, however, still put the number of those affected by
dengue in the capital at 57 and 163 in the entire state.

"We get at least 10 to 15 dengue patients every day and the hospital is
almost full," said Ajay Goenka, a doctor with the private Chirayu Hospital
here. Private practitioners say that the actual number of dengue affected
people will be much higher if the patients in private hospitals and rural
areas are taken into account. Gopal Batini, a doctor with the private
Ayushman Hospital also said that the number of patients would be much
higher than the official figures. "The hospital is almost full because of
dengue," he said.

Director (of health) of Madhya Pradesh government Ashok Sharma told IANS:
"9 people have died from dengue in Madhya Pradesh in the past 3 months,
while 129 others -- of which 57 are in the state capital -- are affected by
the disease. It's true that most dengue patients, as many as 57, were in
the state capital, followed by 33 in Indore, 17 in Balaghat, and 12 in
other districts. 3 people died of dengue in Bhopal and Indore each. One
each succumbed in Ashoknagar, Satna, and Balaghat."

Sharma claimed that necessary steps had been taken to control dengue and
the district medical officers had been directed to remain in contact with
private hospitals and send information about those affected. But a source
in the state health department said: "Surprisingly, none of the
government-run hospitals have single donor platelet phaeresis (SDPP)
machines -- the mechanism required for collection of platelets and plasma
for effective treatment of dengue cases." Secretary of Health Department SR
Mohanty said that procurement of the SDPP machines for Indore, Bhopal,
Ujjain, and Jabalpur hospitals was in the pipeline and they would be made
available soon.

