[2] Sri Lanka (Colombo)
Date: Mon 5 Oct 2009
Source: Daily Mirror [edited]
<http://www.dailymirror.lk/DM_BLOG/Sections/frmNewsDetailView.aspx?ARTID=63655>


The Colombo Municipal Council (CMC) yesterday [4 Oct 2009] warned of a
possible outbreak of dengue after the present rainy season. Chief medical
officer of the CMC Dr Pradeep Kariyawasam told the Daily Mirror yesterday
[4 Oct 2009] that there may be a possible outbreak by November [2009] after
the ongoing rainy season. "An outbreak usually occurs after a rainy season
and there may be one later this year," he said.

He said there had been 52 cases of dengue during the last month. Around 60
per cent of the cases had been between the ages of 5 to 20 [years].

Dr Kariyawasam said the CMC had already launched a school based programme
under which a meeting was held for school principals recently. The
principals were asked to clean their respective schools first and then
clean up the surroundings. He explained that at least a radius of 200 yards
[about 180 m] around the schools have to be kept clean as the flying range
of mosquitoes are usually 150 yards [about 140 m]. He also said the schools
have been asked not to build waterfalls and ponds within the school premises.

"We have taken this stand as the environments in most of the schools in the
city are not in a good condition," he said. He said putting up new
buildings had also polluted the environment in some instances. In some
schools, gutters in the buildings have not been cleaned and mosquito larvae
have been found in these gutters in some schools.

He said classrooms in many schools were dark and it was easy for the
mosquitoes to survive. Dr Kariyawasam said the CMC carried out a similar
school based programme last year [2008] as well and it was a success. He
said he was confident of carrying out a successful campaign this year
[2009] as well.

Meanwhile, he said, volunteers were being trained to carry out the Cuban
system of eradicating dengue.

[byline: Yohan Perera]

