[3] Bangladesh (Dhaka)
Date: Tue 6 Oct 2009
Source: The Daily Star [edited]
<http://www.thedailystar.net/newDesign/news-details.php?nid=108522>


The seasonal illnesses like dengue have been spreading fast in different
parts of the city [Dhaka] for over a month. The city's public and private
hospitals are witnessing an increased number of dengue patients. Private
practitioners are also getting a large number of such patients.

Medical experts said frequent changes in weather and taking contaminated
water are main reasons for the occurrence of such seasonal illnesses.

Some 319 people have been diagnosed with dengue fever till yesterday [5 Oct
2009], chief entomologist of Dhaka City Corporation (DCC) Naseem-Us-Seraj
told The Daily Star. The patients with dengue fever, a viral disease
transmitted by the _Aedes [aegypti]_ mosquito, could be increased now
though generally it reduces during this time (September-October), he said.

Residents of Dhanmondi, Kalabagan, Central Road, Minto Road, Siddeswari,
Muhammadpur, Ganderia, and Mirpur areas are falling victim to dengue virus,
said the DCC official. At least 37 patients from outside of Dhaka got
admitted to the city's different hospitals in last week, he informed.

A total of 300 dengue patients have been admitted to the city hospitals
between June and September [2009], said the control room of the directorate
general of health services.

The breeding ground of _Aedes_ mosquitoes is clear water in containers and
flowerpots, abandoned tires, and coconut shells just around the houses
where the DCC spray teams or cleaners are not allowed. The house owners can
protect themselves from the danger of the deadly disease if they take
initiatives to destroy those breeding grounds, DCC officials said.

